 value of these literary fragments as part of the historical record of the Holocaust and provides informative introductions about when and where each diary was written; the diarist’s biographical, religious, cultural, and economic circumstances; the fate of the diarist; the circumstances of the diary’s discovery. Finally she offers a view of the diary’s significance. An appendix gives details about the known diaries written by young people during this period, more than fifty-five in all. A second appendix provides a study of related materials, such as rewritten and reconstructed diaries, letters, diary-memoirs, and texts by non-Jewish young victims of the war and Nazism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narratives. 0aJewish children in the HolocaustvDiaries. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030009243140uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012741640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300127416/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY